---
import ContentLayout from '../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';

const comparisonPages = [
  {
    href: '/alternatives/splunk-soar',
    title: 'OpenSOAR vs Splunk SOAR',
    description: 'How open-source, Python-native automation compares to a commercial Phantom-era workflow model.',
  },
  {
    href: '/alternatives/xsoar',
    title: 'OpenSOAR vs Palo Alto XSOAR',
    description: 'Compare a self-hosted code-first SOAR with a large commercial marketplace-driven platform.',
  },
  {
    href: '/alternatives/swimlane',
    title: 'OpenSOAR vs Swimlane',
    description: 'A practical comparison between code-first automation and enterprise-focused workflow orchestration.',
  },
  {
    href: '/guides/opensoar-vs-shuffle',
    title: 'OpenSOAR vs Shuffle',
    description: 'The open-source comparison that matters most if you are choosing visual automation versus Python playbooks.',
  },
];

const evaluationSignals = [
  {
    title: 'Choose OpenSOAR if',
    points: [
      'you want playbooks treated like code',
      'your team can own Python workflows',
      'you care about self-hosting and source access',
      'you want to avoid six-figure licensing',
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Choose a commercial platform if',
    points: [
      'you need very broad marketplace coverage immediately',
      'you need packaged enterprise support now',
      'your organization buys platforms faster than it builds systems',
      'you prefer vendor workflow tooling over code ownership',
    ],
  },
];

const editorialLinks = [
  {
    href: '/blog/best-open-source-soar-platforms',
    title: 'Best open-source SOAR platforms',
    description: 'Editorial market view across the open-source landscape.',
  },
  {
    href: '/blog/why-code-first-security-automation-wins',
    title: 'Why code-first automation wins',
    description: 'The engineering case behind the OpenSOAR model.',
  },
];
---

<ContentLayout
  title="OpenSOAR vs Commercial SOAR Platforms: Feature Comparison | OpenSOAR"
  description="Compare OpenSOAR with Splunk SOAR, Palo Alto XSOAR, Swimlane, and other automation models. See where code-first open-source SOAR fits."
  badge="Comparison"
  heading="Compare OpenSOAR"
  subheading="Start with the platform model, not just the checklist. Compare OpenSOAR against commercial SOAR suites and adjacent open-source options."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'Compare', href: '/compare' },
  ]}
>
  <h2>Where to start</h2>
  <p>
    Most teams do not need a giant comparison matrix first. They need to know which platform families are even worth evaluating.
  </p>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 my-6">
    {comparisonPages.map((page) => (
      <a
        href={page.href}
        class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5 transition-colors hover:border-heading/30"
      >
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-heading mb-2">{page.title}</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">{page.description}</p>
      </a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>The core tradeoff</h2>
  <p>
    The real split in this category is not just open-source versus commercial. It is also <strong>code-first versus workflow-builder-first</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    OpenSOAR is built for teams that want automation to behave like software: Python playbooks, Git review, testable logic, and self-hosted control. Commercial suites usually win on marketplace breadth, packaging, and enterprise support, but often at the cost of price and vendor-shaped workflow models.
  </p>

  <h2>Feature comparison</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>OpenSOAR</th>
        <th>Splunk SOAR</th>
        <th>XSOAR</th>
        <th>Swimlane</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>License</td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--positive">Apache 2.0</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Commercial</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Commercial</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Commercial</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Starting price</td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--positive">Free</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Enterprise pricing</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Enterprise pricing</span></td>
        <td><span class="indicator indicator--negative">Enterprise pricing</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Playbook model</td>
        <td>Python</td>
        <td>Visual + Python</td>
        <td>YAML + scripts</td>
        <td>Visual + Python</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Self-hosted</td>
        <td>Yes</td>
        <td>Yes</td>
        <td>Yes / cloud</td>
        <td>Yes / cloud</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>AI-assisted triage</td>
        <td>Built-in</td>
        <td>Add-on / vendor-dependent</td>
        <td>Varies by product tier</td>
        <td>Limited</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Playbook testing</td>
        <td>pytest</td>
        <td>Limited</td>
        <td>Limited</td>
        <td>Limited</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Source access</td>
        <td>Full</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td>No</td>
        <td>No</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout-card callout-card--success">
    <strong>OpenSOAR is the strongest fit for engineering-led teams.</strong> If your team wants to review playbooks in Git, test them in CI, and run the platform in your own infrastructure, the open-source code-first model is usually the cleaner long-term choice.
  </div>

  <h2>How to decide faster</h2>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 my-6">
    {evaluationSignals.map((group) => (
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-heading mb-3">{group.title}</h3>
        <ul>
          {group.points.map((point) => (
            <li>{point}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Where OpenSOAR wins</h2>
  <p>
    OpenSOAR wins on ownership, cost, and workflow durability. If your team expects automations to become an internal system rather than a set of demo diagrams, the code-first model is a real advantage.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Playbooks are readable Python modules, not proprietary workflow shapes.</li>
    <li>Automation changes fit normal software delivery and review workflows.</li>
    <li>You keep your deployment, code, and data without vendor lock-in.</li>
    <li>The pricing model is open-source rather than license-gated.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where commercial platforms still win</h2>
  <p>
    Commercial tools still have real strengths. For some organizations, those strengths matter more than ownership.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Broader integration marketplaces out of the box.</li>
    <li>More mature enterprise packaging and procurement paths.</li>
    <li>Dedicated support and professional services.</li>
    <li>Familiarity for teams already standardized on a specific vendor stack.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Read next</h2>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 my-6">
    {editorialLinks.map((link) => (
      <a
        href={link.href}
        class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5 transition-colors hover:border-heading/30"
      >
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-heading mb-2">{link.title}</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">{link.description}</p>
      </a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <p>
    For product setup, deployment, and playbook behavior, use <a href="https://docs.opensoar.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">docs.opensoar.app</a>.
  </p>
</ContentLayout>
